INSERT INTO `forum_replies` VALUES (1,1,3,'I feel like the difference is that you can have multiple houses (as in buildings) but one home. Home is where you feel you belong to.','2024-11-25 16:08:59','2024-11-25 16:08:59'),(2,1,2,'That makes sense to me. Thank you for your answer @arinc !','2024-11-25 16:41:06','2024-11-25 16:41:06'),(3,2,2,'Himm do you mean the fruit or the brand? 😆','2024-11-25 16:42:41','2024-11-25 16:42:41'),(4,5,4,'It mean apples are health for you and if you consume apples regularly you won\'t have to see a doctor.','2024-11-25 17:19:31','2024-11-25 17:19:31'),(5,5,4,'It doesn\'t have a profound meaning as you might have expected. It just means apples are good for you.','2024-11-25 17:20:00','2024-11-25 17:20:00'),(6,5,4,'Thank you guys. I won\'t be skipping my apples then. :)','2024-11-25 17:20:21','2024-11-25 17:20:21'),(8,6,11,'köprü','2024-11-25 18:59:41','2024-11-25 18:59:41'),(9,11,7,'Ineffable is often used in poetic or philosophical contexts. For example:\n\n\"The beauty of the sunrise over the mountains was ineffable, leaving me in silent awe.\"\nIt carries a sense of deep emotional or spiritual significance that goes beyond mere description.','2024-11-26 12:15:00','2024-11-26 12:15:00'),(10,11,7,'While ineffable and indescribable are similar, ineffable is more often tied to awe-inspiring or sacred experiences. Unspeakable, on the other hand, usually implies something too horrific or terrible to be spoken about. For instance:\n\n\"Her grief was ineffable, felt in every corner of her being.\"\n\"The atrocities committed during the war were unspeakable.\"','2024-11-26 12:15:12','2024-11-26 12:15:12'),(11,11,7,'You can also use ineffable to describe abstract concepts like joy or beauty that feel almost otherworldly. It’s less about the lack of words and more about the grandeur or intensity of the experience.','2024-11-26 12:15:27','2024-11-26 12:15:27'),(12,12,7,'Obfuscate implies intentionality—it’s about deliberately making something confusing or unclear. For example:\n\n\"The politician’s speech seemed designed to obfuscate the real issues.\"\nIn contrast, confuse doesn’t necessarily involve intent.\nReply 2:','2024-11-26 12:15:50','2024-11-26 12:15:50'),(13,12,7,'To illustrate further:\n\nConfuse: \"The complex math problem confused the students.\"\nObfuscate: \"The lawyer used technical jargon to obfuscate the details of the case.\"\nObfuscation often has a sense of deliberate concealment or complexity.','2024-11-26 12:16:20','2024-11-26 12:16:20'),(14,12,7,'You might also encounter obfuscate in technical contexts, like programming, where code is intentionally written in a way that\'s hard to understand, often for security purposes.','2024-11-26 12:16:30','2024-11-26 12:16:30'),(15,13,7,'Ephemeral often describes things that are not just temporary but fleeting, beautiful, or delicate in their impermanence. For example:\n\n\"The cherry blossoms are an ephemeral wonder of spring.\"\nTemporary, on the other hand, is more neutral and practical.','2024-11-26 12:16:42','2024-11-26 12:16:42'),(16,13,7,'Here’s a comparison:\n\nTemporary: \"The office will use temporary staff during the holiday season.\"\nEphemeral: \"The happiness she felt was ephemeral, vanishing as quickly as it came.\"\nNotice how ephemeral has a poetic or poignant tone.','2024-11-26 12:16:49','2024-11-26 12:16:49'),(17,13,7,'You might also use ephemeral in discussions about nature, art, or emotions, emphasizing their fleeting quality. It adds a sense of transience that temporary lacks.','2024-11-26 12:17:05','2024-11-26 12:17:05'),(18,14,7,'You can use ineffable in casual conversations, but it might sound overly formal or dramatic depending on the context. For example, instead of saying, \"The meal was ineffable,\" you could say, \"The meal was so good, it left me speechless.\" However, if you’re talking about a life-changing experience, ineffable might feel more fitting.','2024-11-26 12:24:31','2024-11-26 12:24:31'),(19,14,7,'It’s true that ineffable leans towards poetic usage, but there’s no hard rule against using it casually. For example:\n\n\"The view from the top of the mountain was ineffable.\"\nIt works best when describing something profound or deeply emotional, even in everyday speech.','2024-11-26 12:24:38','2024-11-26 12:24:38'),(20,14,7,'I’d suggest using ineffable sparingly in casual conversations to avoid sounding too formal. That said, if you’re trying to express that something is beyond words, go for it! For example, \"The joy I felt when we reunited after years was ineffable\" could work in a heartfelt chat with a friend.','2024-11-26 12:24:45','2024-11-26 12:24:45'),(21,15,14,'While both words involve future aspirations, they differ in intensity and focus:\n    Ambition refers to a strong desire or determination to achieve a specific goal, often tied to success, power, or progress. It usually implies active effort and persistence. For example, \"Her ambition is to become a CEO.\"\n    Hope is a more general and emotional feeling of expectation or desire for something good to happen, often without a concrete plan or action. For instance, \"I hope it doesn’t rain tomorrow.\"','2024-11-26 12:46:36','2024-11-26 12:46:36'),(22,16,14,'These words all relate to travel, but they have distinct nuances:\n\n    Journey typically emphasizes the process of traveling, especially over a long distance or through a significant experience. It can also be metaphorical, e.g., \"a journey of self-discovery.\"\n    Trip refers to a shorter, often simpler act of traveling to a specific destination and returning, like a vacation or business trip. For example, \"We went on a trip to the beach.\"\n    Voyage usually involves traveling by sea or space, emphasizing the mode of transportation and the adventure aspect, e.g., \"The voyage across the Atlantic was challenging.\"','2024-11-26 12:47:09','2024-11-26 12:47:09'),(23,17,14,'    Serene means calm, peaceful, and untroubled. It can describe both people and places:\n        People: A person described as serene has an inner sense of peace and tranquility, e.g., \"Despite the chaos around her, she remained serene.\"\n        Places: A serene place feels peaceful, quiet, and undisturbed, e.g., \"The lake at sunrise was serene, with no noise or activity.\"\n\nThe word is versatile and often evokes an image of stillness or a lack of disturbance, whether it’s a mood, setting, or even a scene in nature.','2024-11-26 12:47:27','2024-11-26 12:47:27'),(24,16,1,'buvfyi','2024-12-14 21:26:11','2024-12-14 21:26:11'),(27,6,2,'I agree with above comments.','2024-12-16 16:11:55','2024-12-16 16:11:55'),(36,31,24,'Hello arinc, these translations are absolutely correct. You can use them. The only suggestion  I can give you is that do not confuse the \'bishop\' with \'elephant\'. The piece originated from the animal \'elephant\' but the name is \'bishop\'','2024-12-16 19:12:22','2024-12-16 19:12:22'),(37,68,3,'\"I will shield you with my life.\"\nHere, it means protecting. It\'s a verb here.','2024-12-16 19:13:32','2024-12-16 19:13:32'),(38,6,24,'While I agree with the Turkish interpretation here, other meanings of bridge are as follows:\nConnection (Metaphorical use): Establishing a connection between people, ideas, or systems.\nExample: Education acts as a bridge between poverty and opportunity.\n\nIn music (Noun): A different section or section of a song.\nExample: The bridge in the song creates a nice contrast before the final chorus.\n\nBridge (Verb): To fill a gap or to connect two things.\nExample: Technology bridges the gap between distant communities.','2024-12-17 06:40:48','2024-12-17 06:40:48'),(39,92,26,'Bosphorus is a beautiful bridge that connects Asia and Europe.','2024-12-17 07:52:21','2024-12-17 07:52:21'),(40,92,25,'Do you ask the bridge game?','2024-12-17 07:54:08','2024-12-17 07:54:08'),(41,4,29,'Extremely angry 😠 ','2024-12-18 13:34:38','2024-12-18 13:34:38'),(42,12,20,'This is my reply to the post.','2024-1